What is the differences between float ,double and decimal?

1) Float
🔹 What it is
    •  A decimal number with low precision.
    •  Uses scientific notation.
    •  Takes 4 bytes.
🔹 Pros
    •  Very fast.
    •  Uses small memory.
🔹 Cons
    •  Not precise → rounding errors happen.
🔹 Used for
    •  Games
    •  Graphics
    •  Fast calculations where precision doesn’t matter

2) Double
🔹 What it is
    •  A more accurate version of float.
    •  Takes 8 bytes.
    •  Much higher precision.
🔹 Pros
    •  More accurate
    •  Fewer rounding problems
🔹 Cons
    •  Slightly slower
    •  Uses more memory
🔹 Used for
    •  Scientific math
    •  Complex calculations
    •  Anything needing good precision

3) Decimal
🔹 What it is
    •  A number type made for money and financial values.
    •  Takes 16 bytes.
    •  Very high precision because it stores numbers in base-10, like humans, not base-2.
🔹 Pros
    •  Very accurate
    •  No rounding issues with money
🔹 Cons
    •  Slower than float and double
    •  Uses the most memory
🔹 Used for
    •  Prices
    •  Banking systems
    •  Billing and invoices

1) Precision
    •  decimal > double > float

2) Speed
    •  float > double > decimal

3) Memory Size
    •  float → 4 bytes
    •  double → 8 bytes
    •  decimal → 16 bytes

4) Best Use
    •  float → fast, low precision
    •  double → balanced, general math
    •  decimal → money, high accuracy
